1
00:00:02,416 --> 00:00:10,058
So, the story of user research on Destiny is really a microcosm of the story of the development of Destiny as a whole.

2
00:00:11,038 --> 00:00:14,199
And so, just so you can't really talk about Destiny without talking about Halo,

3
00:00:14,599 --> 00:00:18,260
you really can't talk about user research on Destiny without also talking about user research on Halo.

4
00:00:18,920 --> 00:00:22,681
So, for ten years, Bungie made this game called Halo.

5
00:00:23,631 --> 00:00:26,372
and therefore that's what we did our research on.

6
00:00:26,952 --> 00:00:28,533
And we got pretty good at it.

7
00:00:28,573 --> 00:00:30,054
We made five games in that series.

8
00:00:30,674 --> 00:00:32,835
And we pretty much thought we had this job down,

9
00:00:32,895 --> 00:00:34,755
that we knew by the time we got to the fifth one,

10
00:00:34,795 --> 00:00:36,836
we knew exactly how to test the Halo campaign.

11
00:00:37,356 --> 00:00:40,178
We knew how to test competitive multiplayer.

12
00:00:40,358 --> 00:00:42,198
We thought we were pretty good at this.

13
00:00:44,059 --> 00:00:47,000
Unfortunately, it turns out that.

14
00:00:49,397 --> 00:00:51,498
the move to Destiny sort of upped the difficulty quite a bit.

15
00:00:52,098 --> 00:00:54,079
That there were a lot of built-in assumptions

16
00:00:54,239 --> 00:00:55,800
into how we tested Halo,

17
00:00:55,840 --> 00:00:58,882
into the Halo game that made user research easier for us.

18
00:01:00,222 --> 00:01:02,444
Simple things like the fact that each game mode

19
00:01:02,464 --> 00:01:03,544
was a distinct experience,

20
00:01:03,644 --> 00:01:07,906
that you could test the story mode by itself

21
00:01:08,287 --> 00:01:09,387
as an isolated experience

22
00:01:09,527 --> 00:01:11,388
and not have people mixing and matching

23
00:01:11,448 --> 00:01:12,329
in between activities.

24
00:01:13,229 --> 00:01:15,270
The fact that all the missions were always played in the same order.

25
00:01:15,997 --> 00:01:19,197
It turns out to have been a great luxury that we didn't know we had at the time.

26
00:01:20,598 --> 00:01:25,079
Suddenly, we had to make every mission not only fun, but also the right difficulty level,

27
00:01:25,579 --> 00:01:28,620
no matter when people got to it and what state they were in when they got to it.

28
00:01:31,321 --> 00:01:33,181
The missions were more or less independent experiences.

29
00:01:34,467 --> 00:01:39,791
For example, it's very common in game development that Mission 5 isn't working this week, and therefore, that's fine.

30
00:01:39,871 --> 00:01:44,635
We have people play up to Mission 4, we have them read a little paragraph of what happened in the story in Mission 5,

31
00:01:44,835 --> 00:01:48,018
and then we have them proceed on, skip through Mission 6 and let them proceed.

32
00:01:48,999 --> 00:01:50,740
And that works pretty realistically.

33
00:01:51,300 --> 00:01:55,584
In Destiny, suddenly, if you have to skip Mission 5, you haven't gotten any of the experience points.

34
00:01:56,185 --> 00:02:24,957
from that mission. Your character is now under-leveled from mission 6. You don't have any of the gear or the talents that you needed to beat that mission. And suddenly, the entire rest of your testing experience is out of whack because that one piece wasn't there. And Destiny was this very integrated game where all the pieces had to function in order to get good data. A couple of our issues were also sort of metaphysical. On the Halo games, certainly by the time we got to the final ones, we very much knew what kind of game we were making. We knew that

35
00:02:25,551 --> 00:02:28,514
what the modes were going to be, we generally knew what the general mechanics were going to be.

36
00:02:28,534 --> 00:02:33,279
A lot of the big, sort of, hard decisions about game design were already made.

37
00:02:34,820 --> 00:02:37,983
In Destiny, we were discovering a lot of that, and a lot of that was changing over the course of development.

38
00:02:39,745 --> 00:02:42,128
And finally, we knew what kind of players we wanted to play the game.

39
00:02:42,248 --> 00:02:46,692
I mean, the kind of people we wanted to play Halo Reach were pretty much the same kind of people who played Halo 3.

40
00:02:47,053 --> 00:02:49,095
That that was a well-understood audience, that we really had...

41
00:02:50,371 --> 00:02:52,571
had been in touch with for years, they'd played our games,

42
00:02:52,611 --> 00:02:54,632
we had data on exactly how they played our games,

43
00:02:55,312 --> 00:02:58,233
and we had this sort of very good understanding.

44
00:02:58,513 --> 00:03:00,433
Suddenly with Destiny, we had RPG elements.

45
00:03:00,593 --> 00:03:02,694
Okay, should we be recruiting RPG players?

46
00:03:02,854 --> 00:03:03,574
Are we aiming for that?

47
00:03:04,214 --> 00:03:05,314
Are we aiming for MMO players?

48
00:03:05,374 --> 00:03:06,934
Are we aiming for people who play both?

49
00:03:08,255 --> 00:03:09,535
Are these action adventure gamers?

50
00:03:09,555 --> 00:03:12,176
There was a whole bunch of just fundamental assumptions

51
00:03:12,196 --> 00:03:13,756
about our audience that were suddenly called into question.

52
00:03:15,197 --> 00:03:17,338
At the same time, Destiny was just huge.

53
00:03:18,239 --> 00:03:20,020
So we had four planets, all of which

54
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:21,840
were bigger than any of the Halo missions we'd ever done,

55
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:23,641
four enemy races, each as complex

56
00:03:23,701 --> 00:03:26,323
as the Flood of the Covenant, three classes, hundreds

57
00:03:26,363 --> 00:03:28,043
of weapons, story missions, strike missions,

58
00:03:28,784 --> 00:03:30,424
and finally we had patrol and raid,

59
00:03:30,484 --> 00:03:32,846
which were completely new experiences that really

60
00:03:32,906 --> 00:03:35,527
had no analog in anything we'd ever made or tested before.

61
00:03:37,728 --> 00:03:39,029
So this was pretty daunting.

62
00:03:41,768 --> 00:03:44,510
At the same time, this is our first game

63
00:03:44,550 --> 00:03:46,031
we were making outside of Microsoft.

64
00:03:46,152 --> 00:03:49,955
So on previous titles, we'd had the benefit

65
00:03:49,975 --> 00:03:52,577
of Microsoft's lovely user research infrastructure, which

66
00:03:52,637 --> 00:03:56,280
is very elaborate and very well planned out.

67
00:03:56,900 --> 00:03:58,522
And so we had to do this all ourselves.

68
00:03:58,582 --> 00:04:00,223
And we were free of that infrastructure.

69
00:04:00,263 --> 00:04:02,305
So we had to build our own tools at the same time

70
00:04:02,345 --> 00:04:04,046
we were actually testing and building the game.

71
00:04:04,867 --> 00:04:06,689
So building the lab is actually the easy part.

72
00:04:06,749 --> 00:04:07,850
This is a picture of our lab.

73
00:04:08,675 --> 00:04:10,316
It's pretty straightforward, pretty standard compared

74
00:04:10,336 --> 00:04:11,136
to most of the industry.

75
00:04:12,096 --> 00:04:14,757
But the hard part actually is putting people in the lab,

76
00:04:15,278 --> 00:04:16,558
is actually recruiting the participants.

77
00:04:17,098 --> 00:04:19,399
And I'm going to geek out a little bit here.

78
00:04:19,460 --> 00:04:20,060
Please bear with me.

79
00:04:21,520 --> 00:04:23,941
So I know that talking about recruiting participants

80
00:04:24,042 --> 00:04:27,683
is not the sexiest topic in the world, but it really is.

81
00:04:27,703 --> 00:04:30,084
OK, I have one enthusiast.

82
00:04:31,999 --> 00:04:35,282
It really is what defines the limits of your user research

83
00:04:35,302 --> 00:04:37,804
program, because if your recruiting methods don't

84
00:04:37,884 --> 00:04:40,347
get you casual players, you can't run that kind of test.

85
00:04:40,807 --> 00:04:43,069
If your recruiting methods take a few weeks

86
00:04:43,109 --> 00:04:44,891
to get to your participants, suddenly you

87
00:04:44,911 --> 00:04:48,474
have to be testing on a very well-planned, long-term time

88
00:04:48,514 --> 00:04:48,795
scale.

89
00:04:49,796 --> 00:04:53,659
And you can't do snap tests at short notice.

90
00:04:55,901 --> 00:04:59,502
I'm going to talk a little bit about how we went about recruiting participants for Destiny

91
00:04:59,622 --> 00:05:00,062
playtests.

92
00:05:01,102 --> 00:05:02,522
Bear with me, this actually is important.

93
00:05:05,483 --> 00:05:08,364
So first off, we created a sign-up forum on our website to let people volunteer.

94
00:05:08,404 --> 00:05:12,725
We've had over 350,000 people sign up to be playtesters.

95
00:05:13,525 --> 00:05:18,746
And they all give us demographic data, their age, gender, where they live, a bunch of their

96
00:05:18,806 --> 00:05:19,886
attitudes towards games.

97
00:05:22,125 --> 00:05:27,437
They tell us a lot about themselves, and we connect all that to their Halo gameplay data,

98
00:05:27,978 --> 00:05:31,726
and now to their Destiny gameplay data, so we know who they were in their actual play

99
00:05:31,766 --> 00:05:32,809
as well as who they said they were.

100
00:05:35,169 --> 00:05:37,151
And this led us, when we wanted to run a study,

101
00:05:37,191 --> 00:05:39,534
we could then pull exactly the profile participant we needed.

102
00:05:39,554 --> 00:05:40,895
We could say, OK, we want people who've

103
00:05:41,476 --> 00:05:42,897
beaten the campaign on Legendary.

104
00:05:43,318 --> 00:05:45,980
We want people who played less than an hour of multiplayer,

105
00:05:46,040 --> 00:05:47,882
people who played more than 100 hours of multiplayer.

106
00:05:48,423 --> 00:05:52,147
We could use this survey data to say exactly where they were,

107
00:05:52,367 --> 00:05:55,290
all their demographics, and their gameplay data to know

108
00:05:55,350 --> 00:05:56,811
how they played our games.

109
00:05:58,165 --> 00:06:01,429
We pull that sample of people and then send them an online survey to schedule them.

110
00:06:01,509 --> 00:06:02,330
So this is unusual.

111
00:06:02,430 --> 00:06:06,175
Most recruiting agencies call up all their participants on the phone and screen them

112
00:06:06,195 --> 00:06:11,661
that way, which tends to be a very manpower-intensive process and take a lot of time, and ends up

113
00:06:11,741 --> 00:06:15,546
costing something on the order of $200 a participant to recruit a participant this way.

114
00:06:17,886 --> 00:06:23,949
Because we could send a survey that would screen them and schedule them and slot them into their time slots,

115
00:06:24,929 --> 00:06:28,911
we could basically schedule a study with very little work, maybe a couple of hours of work total by the researcher.

116
00:06:29,883 --> 00:06:31,143
and on very short notice.

117
00:06:31,183 --> 00:06:33,704
So anywhere from a week to three days.

118
00:06:34,504 --> 00:06:37,245
We did a couple of studies on two or one day notice.

119
00:06:38,566 --> 00:06:40,266
We've never done a same day study

120
00:06:40,286 --> 00:06:41,807
where we kicked off the scheduling in the morning

121
00:06:41,847 --> 00:06:43,367
and had people show up in the evening.

122
00:06:44,148 --> 00:06:45,468
The system certainly would support that.

123
00:06:45,948 --> 00:06:47,249
But I don't want my designers thinking

124
00:06:47,289 --> 00:06:48,729
they can drop things on me in the last minute.

125
00:06:50,170 --> 00:06:50,570
Don't tell them.

126
00:06:50,890 --> 00:06:51,390
I trust you guys.

127
00:06:53,256 --> 00:06:55,398
And one other geek note I'll mention on this,

128
00:06:56,198 --> 00:06:59,001
not all survey tools handle quotas the same way.

129
00:06:59,041 --> 00:07:00,983
So not all survey tools are necessarily

130
00:07:01,043 --> 00:07:02,664
suitable for this kind of scheduling setup.

131
00:07:03,324 --> 00:07:04,726
So there's some fine technical details

132
00:07:04,766 --> 00:07:06,587
in how they handle them that make them more or less suitable.

133
00:07:09,029 --> 00:07:09,930
So we had all these systems.

134
00:07:10,941 --> 00:07:12,362
working and they had them all connected together.

135
00:07:12,402 --> 00:07:15,463
So we could have this one system that would let us pull participants that we wanted,

136
00:07:15,843 --> 00:07:19,365
schedule them, screen them out, and have them show up in the lab.

137
00:07:19,385 --> 00:07:21,146
And we had really good success with this.

138
00:07:22,007 --> 00:07:26,089
We scheduled something like 1,400 participants over the course of four years for this game,

139
00:07:27,129 --> 00:07:28,690
saving us on the order of $400,000

140
00:07:30,591 --> 00:07:33,412
by doing all the scheduling in-house using an automated system.

141
00:07:35,133 --> 00:07:37,775
Now, you may be right to be skeptical that...

142
00:07:39,567 --> 00:07:41,288
our participants were probably a little biased,

143
00:07:41,348 --> 00:07:43,510
that these were people who signed up on a Bungie website

144
00:07:43,530 --> 00:07:45,031
to test a Bungie game in a Bungie building.

145
00:07:45,571 --> 00:07:47,272
So yes, they were fans.

146
00:07:48,713 --> 00:07:50,634
But we dealt with that bias in a couple of different ways.

147
00:07:50,855 --> 00:07:53,656
First off, a lot of the questions we were asking them

148
00:07:53,737 --> 00:07:56,258
weren't the kind of questions that would be affected by bias.

149
00:07:56,298 --> 00:07:59,560
So if we asked them, do you like Destiny better than Call of Duty,

150
00:08:00,301 --> 00:08:01,722
yes, their answers would be biased.

151
00:08:02,542 --> 00:08:05,364
But if you asked them, do you like Mission 5 better than Mission 6?

152
00:08:06,578 --> 00:08:10,321
there's no reason to believe that their bias would affect one mission more than another.

153
00:08:10,601 --> 00:08:11,582
So it sort of cancelled out.

154
00:08:12,643 --> 00:08:15,865
We also did some comparison studies where we actually did use outside recruiting agencies

155
00:08:16,085 --> 00:08:19,188
and found that the internally recruited participants gave us essentially the same data.

156
00:08:20,409 --> 00:08:22,591
Particularly directional data,

157
00:08:22,611 --> 00:08:24,672
that if the internal people said a mission was too hard,

158
00:08:24,712 --> 00:08:27,314
the external people said it was too hard, and so on.

159
00:08:27,554 --> 00:08:30,997
And their rankings of what were their favorite missions and least favorite missions were all identical.

160
00:08:32,846 --> 00:08:34,587
We also did some post-stratification work

161
00:08:35,208 --> 00:08:38,150
to look at how our sample differed

162
00:08:38,190 --> 00:08:39,170
from the real population.

163
00:08:39,210 --> 00:08:42,733
So along the x-axis here are different player types,

164
00:08:43,173 --> 00:08:45,535
and the y-axis is how common they were in our sample

165
00:08:45,615 --> 00:08:46,575
and the general population.

166
00:08:46,635 --> 00:08:48,457
And as you can see, type 1 players

167
00:08:48,497 --> 00:08:49,838
were very common in our sample.

168
00:08:49,878 --> 00:08:52,539
Those are the online engaged players.

169
00:08:53,300 --> 00:08:55,021
But because we knew how common they

170
00:08:55,041 --> 00:08:57,203
were in the general population, we could weight their answers

171
00:08:57,943 --> 00:08:59,784
and give them the proper.

172
00:09:01,675 --> 00:09:03,136
the proper impact on our ratings.

173
00:09:04,677 --> 00:09:06,679
So the first thing we did with all this wonderful data

174
00:09:07,380 --> 00:09:11,703
was to segment the Halo Reach player population,

175
00:09:11,723 --> 00:09:13,685
say how many types of Halo players there are.

176
00:09:14,466 --> 00:09:15,727
And there's a bunch of different ways to do this.

177
00:09:15,947 --> 00:09:18,089
And the way we ended up settling on

178
00:09:18,269 --> 00:09:19,990
was doing it by play habits, that we're

179
00:09:20,230 --> 00:09:23,673
saying if you have a population of players,

180
00:09:23,853 --> 00:09:26,195
are there subtypes of similar players

181
00:09:26,235 --> 00:09:27,577
that play the game in the same way?

182
00:09:29,315 --> 00:09:30,295
There's a bunch of different algorithms,

183
00:09:30,335 --> 00:09:34,818
and we can segment them by things like demographics,

184
00:09:34,878 --> 00:09:37,340
their ages, where they live, all that kind of things.

185
00:09:37,420 --> 00:09:40,122
But what we ended up settling on and using mostly

186
00:09:40,282 --> 00:09:44,085
is how they played the game, what proportion of time

187
00:09:44,125 --> 00:09:46,066
they spent in the different game modes in Halo.

188
00:09:47,105 --> 00:09:49,006
So some people spend lots of time one mode,

189
00:09:49,026 --> 00:09:50,247
some people spend more balanced.

190
00:09:50,727 --> 00:09:52,127
But we could use that to basically give

191
00:09:52,147 --> 00:09:53,528
each player a behavioral fingerprint

192
00:09:53,868 --> 00:09:56,469
and then group players by having who had similar fingerprints

193
00:09:56,489 --> 00:10:01,291
to say there are a small set of specific subtypes of players.

194
00:10:03,392 --> 00:10:04,853
And one thing I'll say about this process,

195
00:10:04,893 --> 00:10:07,394
so in case you decide to do this yourself,

196
00:10:08,254 --> 00:10:11,576
I'm not going to talk about the technical algorithms so much.

197
00:10:12,820 --> 00:10:16,582
I found the process of segmenting the player base to be almost more interesting than the

198
00:10:16,622 --> 00:10:17,722
final answers themselves.

199
00:10:17,863 --> 00:10:22,165
I mean, it's very satisfying to say there are five types of players and here are the

200
00:10:22,245 --> 00:10:25,207
mathematically the best five clusters of players.

201
00:10:25,847 --> 00:10:27,288
But when you're, uh...

202
00:10:28,709 --> 00:10:30,950
doing the analysis, you're trying a lot of different types.

203
00:10:30,990 --> 00:10:33,552
You're saying, well what happens if I factor in age

204
00:10:33,652 --> 00:10:34,393
or take out age?

205
00:10:34,693 --> 00:10:37,575
What happens if I split up story mode

206
00:10:37,675 --> 00:10:40,837
from just one bucket into two buckets?

207
00:10:40,917 --> 00:10:41,698
Oh, sorry.

208
00:10:42,298 --> 00:10:44,440
Into two buckets by difficulty level.

209
00:10:46,195 --> 00:10:49,497
And the answers you get change as you change the question.

210
00:10:49,918 --> 00:10:52,639
And how those answers change are almost more interesting

211
00:10:52,679 --> 00:10:54,621
than the final answer themselves and tell you

212
00:10:54,661 --> 00:10:56,382
a lot about the texture of your player base

213
00:10:56,482 --> 00:10:59,604
in a way that just the there are only five players answer

214
00:10:59,724 --> 00:11:00,284
doesn't tell you.

215
00:11:01,985 --> 00:11:04,527
So one model might say, OK, there

216
00:11:04,547 --> 00:11:05,448
are three types of players.

217
00:11:05,488 --> 00:11:07,389
There's red, blue, and green players.

218
00:11:08,302 --> 00:11:12,865
Let's say we add in a new factor into the clustering algorithm

219
00:11:12,885 --> 00:11:15,327
to chew on, and suddenly that green population

220
00:11:15,367 --> 00:11:16,868
splits into two subpopulations.

221
00:11:16,988 --> 00:11:19,109
And now the algorithm says the best fit

222
00:11:19,149 --> 00:11:20,891
is having four types of players.

223
00:11:21,671 --> 00:11:23,072
The really interesting thing here isn't,

224
00:11:23,532 --> 00:11:25,114
are there three kinds of players or four?

225
00:11:25,634 --> 00:11:27,395
It's, why did that happen?

226
00:11:27,675 --> 00:11:29,377
Why did that factor make that difference?

227
00:11:29,657 --> 00:11:31,818
And why did those players group together or split apart?

228
00:11:32,717 --> 00:11:36,500
And all those kinds of little texture moments to your data,

229
00:11:37,040 --> 00:11:39,423
I found really important and interesting.

230
00:11:41,024 --> 00:11:43,766
And I'll stop teasing you and talk about the actual type

231
00:11:43,786 --> 00:11:44,127
we found.

232
00:11:44,967 --> 00:11:46,729
So we found there were, depending

233
00:11:46,749 --> 00:11:49,331
on how you counted, either 5, 10, or 3 types of players.

234
00:11:49,952 --> 00:11:51,834
So there were three overarching categories,

235
00:11:51,854 --> 00:11:53,195
that there were campaigners, there

236
00:11:53,215 --> 00:11:55,317
were people who played Halo primarily for the campaign,

237
00:11:55,357 --> 00:11:57,258
then played multiplayer for a little bit and dribbled off.

238
00:11:58,347 --> 00:12:01,527
There were omnivores who played in a very balanced way,

239
00:12:01,787 --> 00:12:03,748
spreading their time across multiple game modes.

240
00:12:04,768 --> 00:12:05,468
And there were specialists.

241
00:12:05,488 --> 00:12:07,668
There were people who loved one game mode

242
00:12:07,728 --> 00:12:10,569
and just played it for like 90% of their playtime.

243
00:12:11,549 --> 00:12:14,490
Some examples might be capture the flag specialists,

244
00:12:14,570 --> 00:12:16,750
or people who played only custom games with friends.

245
00:12:18,311 --> 00:12:20,091
And each individual subtype of specialist

246
00:12:20,131 --> 00:12:23,152
was very rare, only a percentage or two of the population.

247
00:12:23,192 --> 00:12:24,932
But taken together as a group, they

248
00:12:25,132 --> 00:12:26,572
made up a substantial minority.

249
00:12:28,093 --> 00:12:30,253
And so as we were analyzing this data and thinking about it

250
00:12:30,533 --> 00:12:35,394
and incorporating it into our plan for Destiny,

251
00:12:35,574 --> 00:12:37,554
the idea of the omnivores really struck home,

252
00:12:37,594 --> 00:12:38,695
the idea that there were players who

253
00:12:38,735 --> 00:12:40,415
were playing in this balanced way,

254
00:12:41,155 --> 00:12:43,075
spreading their time across multiple game modes.

255
00:12:44,236 --> 00:12:48,716
And it had always been the idea for Destiny

256
00:12:48,756 --> 00:12:50,477
that there would be a variety of activities,

257
00:12:50,537 --> 00:12:53,597
that one of the essential design pillars

258
00:12:53,677 --> 00:12:56,358
was an activity for every mood, that we would have intense.

259
00:12:57,188 --> 00:13:01,930
competitive activities, and very calm activities, story missions that you were guaranteed to

260
00:13:01,950 --> 00:13:06,552
win if you spent enough time, and raids that were intended to be deliberately very hard.

261
00:13:08,052 --> 00:13:12,254
But once we had the idea of the Omnivore, we started thinking that

262
00:13:13,128 --> 00:13:16,590
We really want to encourage people to play not just the right activity for their mood,

263
00:13:16,611 --> 00:13:19,933
but also to play a variety of activities and to not specialize too much.

264
00:13:20,794 --> 00:13:23,877
This was connected in our heads to the idea of the buffet effect from psychology.

265
00:13:24,357 --> 00:13:28,641
The idea that if you have one flavor of food, like a giant bowl of white rice,

266
00:13:29,441 --> 00:13:34,946
you'll feel full and you'll get sick of it sooner than if you have five flavors or ten flavors out in front of you.

267
00:13:34,986 --> 00:13:37,448
That's why when you go to a buffet you always end up eating too much.

268
00:13:38,249 --> 00:13:43,053
because it takes longer to get bored of having so many different flavors and so many different tastes.

269
00:13:44,314 --> 00:13:48,738
And talking about in terms of food, it feels a little negative and has some bad associations,

270
00:13:48,818 --> 00:13:51,560
but if you think about it in terms of things like CrossFit,

271
00:13:51,680 --> 00:13:54,123
where you go to the gym and there's a workout of the day up on the board,

272
00:13:54,583 --> 00:13:58,226
and it's randomly determined and you won't get bored.

273
00:13:58,266 --> 00:14:00,868
It's not like you're, okay, I'm going to the gym and I'm going to swim laps,

274
00:14:00,969 --> 00:14:03,651
and I know I'm going to swim laps until my eyes bleed.

275
00:14:04,966 --> 00:14:06,266
there's something different every time,

276
00:14:06,387 --> 00:14:08,307
and you never get used to the routine.

277
00:14:09,208 --> 00:14:12,829
And it makes for a more robust athlete.

278
00:14:14,270 --> 00:14:16,010
And other games have done this sort of thing before.

279
00:14:16,290 --> 00:14:18,351
They've deliberately set out to encourage omnivores.

280
00:14:18,411 --> 00:14:21,052
So if you play Hearthstone, which I do too much,

281
00:14:23,053 --> 00:14:25,194
they have their daily quest where they say,

282
00:14:25,274 --> 00:14:27,695
OK, we're going to give you extra gold if you play this class

283
00:14:27,735 --> 00:14:28,755
you don't normally play.

284
00:14:29,335 --> 00:14:31,276
And so maybe you never play a priest deck,

285
00:14:31,376 --> 00:14:33,197
but you have a daily quest for it, and OK, yeah,

286
00:14:33,217 --> 00:14:33,877
I'll go look it up.

287
00:14:34,754 --> 00:14:36,615
I'll go look up a priest deck and give it a shot.

288
00:14:37,155 --> 00:14:40,018
And that way, if your other deck that you normally play

289
00:14:40,058 --> 00:14:42,460
stops working, well, you had that priest deck

290
00:14:42,480 --> 00:14:43,260
you played yesterday.

291
00:14:43,661 --> 00:14:44,681
Maybe I'll play that instead.

292
00:14:45,914 --> 00:14:48,716
that being a broader player, a more robust,

293
00:14:49,037 --> 00:14:50,678
a more omnivorous player, actually

294
00:14:50,698 --> 00:14:51,879
makes you a more robust player.

295
00:14:52,359 --> 00:14:54,701
If you only play one game mode, in some ways

296
00:14:54,721 --> 00:14:55,522
you're very fragile.

297
00:14:56,062 --> 00:14:57,523
If that game mode stops working for you,

298
00:14:57,543 --> 00:14:58,984
if it stops having rewards for you,

299
00:14:59,425 --> 00:15:02,227
if it stops being possible for you,

300
00:15:02,307 --> 00:15:05,429
if you only play cooperatively with your friend online

301
00:15:05,449 --> 00:15:08,892
and your friend stops playing, you probably stop playing too.

302
00:15:09,352 --> 00:15:10,833
But if that cooperative play is just

303
00:15:11,013 --> 00:15:15,016
one segment of a wider array of activities you engage in.

304
00:15:16,077 --> 00:15:19,160
you'll probably be more likely to keep playing even

305
00:15:19,300 --> 00:15:21,862
after one segment of that stops working for you.

306
00:15:22,943 --> 00:15:25,144
And therefore, if the decision was really

307
00:15:25,184 --> 00:15:28,627
made to slope the floor towards helping all players play

308
00:15:28,667 --> 00:15:31,870
like omnivores, and please note my phrasing on this,

309
00:15:32,310 --> 00:15:34,111
we are not requiring players to be omnivores.

310
00:15:34,131 --> 00:15:35,512
We are not forcing them to be omnivores.

311
00:15:35,873 --> 00:15:37,594
We're just always making it a little bit easier

312
00:15:37,614 --> 00:15:41,877
to play that way than to play as a focused specialist player.

313
00:15:42,338 --> 00:15:44,780
And we're going to give little nudges to you to go play

314
00:15:44,960 --> 00:15:45,180
as a.

315
00:15:46,132 --> 00:15:47,393
to play in a more balanced way.

316
00:15:47,493 --> 00:15:50,235
So for example, even if you're playing a warlock in Destiny,

317
00:15:50,595 --> 00:15:52,436
we'll drop gear for other classes

318
00:15:52,476 --> 00:15:54,658
to just give you a little nudge towards trying

319
00:15:54,698 --> 00:15:55,358
another character.

320
00:15:56,039 --> 00:15:57,680
So it's like, oh, I don't normally play a titan,

321
00:15:57,720 --> 00:15:59,081
but hey, I got this really cool helmet.

322
00:15:59,381 --> 00:16:00,122
Yeah, I'll give it a shot.

323
00:16:01,262 --> 00:16:02,964
And we'll just encourage you to be playing

324
00:16:02,984 --> 00:16:04,024
in a more balanced way.

325
00:16:05,966 --> 00:16:07,427
Probably the extreme example of this

326
00:16:07,507 --> 00:16:10,829
is the exotic bounties, where we, for example,

327
00:16:10,849 --> 00:16:11,510
the thorn bounty.

328
00:16:12,119 --> 00:16:16,003
where we require players to both do strikes and PvP to get this really good weapon.

329
00:16:17,865 --> 00:16:21,169
I'm not the only person to blame for the Thorn Bounty, if you've had it and hate it,

330
00:16:22,310 --> 00:16:24,913
but certainly this was one of the components that led to that idea.

331
00:16:27,316 --> 00:16:29,597
So we did a lot of research on Destiny,

332
00:16:29,617 --> 00:16:31,178
and we knew we wanted to start really early.

333
00:16:31,238 --> 00:16:34,079
So this chart shows the research studies

334
00:16:34,099 --> 00:16:36,300
we did per month on a number of our different games,

335
00:16:37,300 --> 00:16:40,082
starting from launch at the far right side of the graph

336
00:16:40,282 --> 00:16:41,622
and going backwards in time to the left.

337
00:16:42,523 --> 00:16:44,303
And so we really wanted to start early on Destiny.

338
00:16:44,824 --> 00:16:47,105
And we knew we wanted to get a lot.

339
00:16:47,285 --> 00:16:49,706
We had these big open design questions,

340
00:16:50,146 --> 00:16:52,267
and we knew we wanted to get the game in the lab early

341
00:16:52,307 --> 00:16:54,328
and do a lot of early impact.

342
00:16:55,835 --> 00:16:59,118
Unfortunately, there's some very real concerns about,

343
00:16:59,578 --> 00:17:02,120
OK, you're testing the game four years before it comes out.

344
00:17:02,140 --> 00:17:05,483
A leak is much worse than it's going to be later on.

345
00:17:06,924 --> 00:17:08,725
Because we really didn't want the first information

346
00:17:08,765 --> 00:17:10,527
out there about Destiny to be coming out of our labs.

347
00:17:11,848 --> 00:17:13,349
So we upped our security quite a bit.

348
00:17:14,090 --> 00:17:15,731
This is Jerry, our head of security.

349
00:17:18,333 --> 00:17:19,394
This picture was actually voted one

350
00:17:19,414 --> 00:17:21,016
of the eight manliest pictures on the internet.

351
00:17:21,716 --> 00:17:22,797
And I fully agree.

352
00:17:24,797 --> 00:17:26,397
But we upped our security quite a bit.

353
00:17:27,118 --> 00:17:28,379
Our players go through metal detectors

354
00:17:28,399 --> 00:17:29,979
to make sure they're not bringing any recording devices

355
00:17:29,999 --> 00:17:30,460
into the lab.

356
00:17:30,500 --> 00:17:31,800
We make them lock up their cell phones.

357
00:17:32,921 --> 00:17:34,382
They are never left alone with the game.

358
00:17:36,083 --> 00:17:41,306
And we do our testing platforms are very highly locked down

359
00:17:41,346 --> 00:17:43,047
to make sure that no one could take a screenshot

360
00:17:43,067 --> 00:17:44,567
and email it to themselves or anything.

361
00:17:47,871 --> 00:17:50,232
Our security processes are probably overkill in a strictly

362
00:17:50,272 --> 00:17:53,592
sort of practical sense, but they let the studio trust us

363
00:17:54,093 --> 00:17:56,553
to put the game in the lab probably something like six

364
00:17:56,593 --> 00:17:58,154
months earlier than they would have otherwise.

365
00:17:58,534 --> 00:18:00,994
So we got six months more impact on the game

366
00:18:01,034 --> 00:18:03,835
than we would have if we hadn't gone to such elaborate lengths

367
00:18:03,875 --> 00:18:04,375
on security.

368
00:18:06,516 --> 00:18:07,856
And one of the first things we found

369
00:18:07,916 --> 00:18:10,717
was we were testing the game is that there

370
00:18:10,737 --> 00:18:11,777
was a split between.

371
00:18:12,897 --> 00:18:15,458
testing the game as a whole and testing it in specific parts.

372
00:18:16,679 --> 00:18:19,601
And this is connected in my mind to the idea of the Heisenberg principle, not the

373
00:18:19,661 --> 00:18:21,742
breaking bad Heisenberg, the real Heisenberg.

374
00:18:22,683 --> 00:18:26,405
The idea that the more precisely you know the position of a particle, the less you

375
00:18:26,425 --> 00:18:27,345
know about its velocity,

376
00:18:28,006 --> 00:18:30,327
because measuring one interferes with the other.

377
00:18:30,908 --> 00:18:32,068
And we really found if we...

378
00:18:33,228 --> 00:18:36,109
we couldn't test both the game as a holistic unit

379
00:18:36,609 --> 00:18:40,070
and any specific mission or part of the game at the same time.

380
00:18:40,630 --> 00:18:43,011
Because if we wanted to test the game as a whole, we said,

381
00:18:43,051 --> 00:18:45,511
OK, just sit down, go ahead and play.

382
00:18:45,991 --> 00:18:48,152
Well, we couldn't guarantee that enough people would play

383
00:18:48,172 --> 00:18:50,453
any part of the game to give us real statistical power

384
00:18:50,513 --> 00:18:51,313
to say anything about it.

385
00:18:51,953 --> 00:18:54,554
And even if they did, if half of them

386
00:18:54,614 --> 00:18:57,595
went straight to that mission by just skipping straight there,

387
00:18:58,773 --> 00:19:02,497
They're going to be underleveled and half of them go off and do something else for three hours and then come back.

388
00:19:02,698 --> 00:19:03,458
They're overleveled.

389
00:19:04,239 --> 00:19:11,747
How do you combine that information to get a real mathematical picture of how hard that mission is or how fun that mission is

390
00:19:12,388 --> 00:19:16,332
when players are coming at it from such a variety of angles?

391
00:19:17,795 --> 00:19:20,637
So we ended up basically testing every piece of content multiple times,

392
00:19:21,238 --> 00:19:22,359
and pretty much in parallel.

393
00:19:22,399 --> 00:19:24,601
The idea that we would test it very specifically,

394
00:19:24,841 --> 00:19:25,882
and under controlled conditions,

395
00:19:25,922 --> 00:19:29,545
so we had the statistical power to make strong claims about it,

396
00:19:29,906 --> 00:19:31,267
about its difficulty, and so on.

397
00:19:32,228 --> 00:19:35,891
And also test it as part of a larger, holistic, free-form test,

398
00:19:35,911 --> 00:19:37,732
where people were allowed to progress naturally.

399
00:19:38,813 --> 00:19:40,975
And so to give you an example of a free-form test...

400
00:19:42,024 --> 00:19:42,824
the kind of results we got.

401
00:19:42,844 --> 00:19:46,006
So this is, each column here is a mission

402
00:19:46,526 --> 00:19:47,787
in our story mode.

403
00:19:48,527 --> 00:19:50,789
And these are the Earth missions, Moon, Mars, Venus,

404
00:19:50,829 --> 00:19:51,109
Mars.

405
00:19:52,109 --> 00:19:55,291
The black lines represent the ideal level

406
00:19:55,591 --> 00:19:57,112
for the characters going to that mission.

407
00:19:57,172 --> 00:19:58,513
That's the level the enemies are.

408
00:19:59,093 --> 00:20:01,035
So, and the blue dots represent the level

409
00:20:01,075 --> 00:20:03,076
the players were when they got to that mission

410
00:20:03,356 --> 00:20:04,296
in this particular play test.

411
00:20:05,213 --> 00:20:07,075
And so as you can see, people start off on track,

412
00:20:07,275 --> 00:20:08,697
missions one, two, three, pretty good.

413
00:20:08,877 --> 00:20:10,999
Then they're under-leveled for mission four, five,

414
00:20:11,659 --> 00:20:12,801
start to catch up on moon.

415
00:20:12,921 --> 00:20:13,942
They're under-leveled on Venus.

416
00:20:14,002 --> 00:20:15,283
And then by the time they get to Mars,

417
00:20:15,323 --> 00:20:16,284
they're very under-leveled.

418
00:20:17,385 --> 00:20:19,467
And in particular, that particular

419
00:20:21,007 --> 00:20:24,728
level jump between Venus and Mars was a deliberate design decision.

420
00:20:25,328 --> 00:20:28,829
And the idea was that people would get there, they'd look at the Mars missions and see that

421
00:20:28,849 --> 00:20:32,770
they were higher level than they were, and they'd say, okay, well I can either go straight

422
00:20:32,790 --> 00:20:37,031
into those missions and have them be a little challenging, or I can go do something else for a while and come back.

423
00:20:37,091 --> 00:20:40,871
I'll go do a strike, I'll go do some PVP, and I'll come back and I'll be the appropriate level.

424
00:20:42,372 --> 00:20:44,952
And as it turns out, players didn't even see

425
00:20:44,972 --> 00:20:48,033
this as a choice. They just plowed straight from one story mission to the other.

426
00:20:49,153 --> 00:20:49,733
The way people can...

427
00:20:50,776 --> 00:20:52,657
and just said, oh, I guess the game gets really hard now.

428
00:20:54,617 --> 00:20:58,079
And the way people ended up consuming the story missions

429
00:20:58,139 --> 00:21:00,460
almost reminds me of the way people watch television

430
00:21:00,480 --> 00:21:01,360
series on Netflix.

431
00:21:01,900 --> 00:21:04,981
The new series of House of Cards opened, I guess,

432
00:21:05,021 --> 00:21:05,722
this weekend, right?

433
00:21:06,162 --> 00:21:07,562
And they drop all the episodes at once,

434
00:21:07,623 --> 00:21:09,703
and people just sit down, watch it all in a weekend,

435
00:21:09,743 --> 00:21:10,984
and just hate themselves afterwards.

436
00:21:11,764 --> 00:21:15,486
And that's pretty much what seems to happen with story missions, is people, even when

437
00:21:15,506 --> 00:21:19,287
we say, there's other stuff to do, go, go try something else and come back, it'll still

438
00:21:19,307 --> 00:21:19,587
be here.

439
00:21:20,148 --> 00:21:22,849
They still want to just plow through story mission after story mission.

440
00:21:23,329 --> 00:21:26,390
And so we had to actually sort of correct our assumption and make it, Mars a little

441
00:21:26,430 --> 00:21:29,392
more accessible than it actually ended up being, it was in this test.

442
00:21:31,052 --> 00:21:32,733
So this is an example of our freeform testing.

443
00:21:34,677 --> 00:21:35,518
the holistic testing.

444
00:21:35,638 --> 00:21:38,119
And then, for example, of precision testing,

445
00:21:38,260 --> 00:21:41,482
this is a difficulty for each of the story missions in Destiny.

446
00:21:41,562 --> 00:21:44,383
So again, these are Earth, Moon, Venus, and Mars.

447
00:21:44,984 --> 00:21:47,946
And each column is a mission, and the length of the bar

448
00:21:48,186 --> 00:21:49,827
is how hard that mission was.

449
00:21:49,887 --> 00:21:51,388
So if the bar is going up, it's too hard.

450
00:21:51,408 --> 00:21:53,889
If the bar is going down, it's too easy.

451
00:21:54,630 --> 00:21:56,231
And we did this kind of testing repeatedly

452
00:21:56,371 --> 00:21:58,352
over the course of development, because things

453
00:21:58,392 --> 00:21:59,453
would change all the time.

454
00:21:59,533 --> 00:22:01,294
Even if nothing had changed in the mission itself,

455
00:22:02,818 --> 00:22:05,740
There would be small changes to combatants, there would be changes to other mechanics.

456
00:22:05,800 --> 00:22:10,622
If suddenly ammunition was dropping less frequently, a mission could get more difficult,

457
00:22:10,962 --> 00:22:12,823
even if the mission designers hadn't changed anything.

458
00:22:12,863 --> 00:22:17,305
So we did a lot of repeated testing to make sure that things were staying trued up all the way along.

459
00:22:18,006 --> 00:22:21,167
And by and large, we were pretty successful in hammering down the difficulty spikes,

460
00:22:21,847 --> 00:22:24,349
although there were still a few in the released game.

461
00:22:25,809 --> 00:22:29,411
This is the Chamber of Night mission is one that stands out in my mind.

462
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:31,932
This is Telthor the Unborn. He's a cutie.

463
00:22:33,757 --> 00:22:35,259
And so this is the final mission on the moon.

464
00:22:36,319 --> 00:22:40,623
And this is actually, this mission is actually an example of a design pattern that we used

465
00:22:40,663 --> 00:22:43,686
a couple of different times that ended up being very difficult for a lot of players,

466
00:22:44,186 --> 00:22:48,910
where we basically lock the player in a round room, there's limited cover, and there's multiple

467
00:22:48,950 --> 00:22:52,153
waves of enemies you have to beat with finally a boss Telthor at the end.

468
00:22:53,134 --> 00:22:55,136
And if you die at any point in that process...

469
00:22:57,237 --> 00:22:59,499
you have to start over from the beginning of the encounter

470
00:22:59,719 --> 00:23:00,660
and do all the waves again.

471
00:23:00,680 --> 00:23:02,201
There's no save points in between waves.

472
00:23:03,162 --> 00:23:05,344
And this really ended up being a hard skill check

473
00:23:05,424 --> 00:23:08,106
because there wasn't really a whole lot of options

474
00:23:08,126 --> 00:23:10,788
for players to handle this encounter differently.

475
00:23:11,168 --> 00:23:12,710
You couldn't, because you're locked in the room

476
00:23:12,730 --> 00:23:14,831
with the enemies, you really couldn't hang back and snipe.

477
00:23:15,392 --> 00:23:17,974
You couldn't sort of kill a few and then run away and come

478
00:23:18,014 --> 00:23:18,254
back.

479
00:23:18,894 --> 00:23:20,296
It was you're in there with them,

480
00:23:20,436 --> 00:23:21,957
and you're either good enough to survive or not.

481
00:23:23,158 --> 00:23:24,679
And this wasn't a huge blocker.

482
00:23:24,739 --> 00:23:25,620
I mean, we didn't lose.

483
00:23:26,626 --> 00:23:30,447
a majority of players or anything, but we lost a few percentage points of players in

484
00:23:30,467 --> 00:23:36,109
the campaign when they just weren't good enough at that moment to come to beat that encounter

485
00:23:36,949 --> 00:23:39,010
and didn't even come back after they were higher level.

486
00:23:42,931 --> 00:23:47,373
So that's all I'm going to talk about is those two types of testing, the holistic and reductionist

487
00:23:47,393 --> 00:23:47,733
testing.

488
00:23:51,650 --> 00:23:52,751
I'm going to talk for the rest of this talk,

489
00:23:52,771 --> 00:23:54,132
I'm going to talk about some special topics

490
00:23:54,192 --> 00:23:55,653
and some particularly interesting research

491
00:23:55,693 --> 00:23:56,633
findings about Destiny.

492
00:23:57,174 --> 00:24:00,096
But please make no mistake, this kind of testing

493
00:24:00,116 --> 00:24:02,758
that I'm showing here was the majority

494
00:24:02,778 --> 00:24:03,738
of what we did on Destiny.

495
00:24:03,758 --> 00:24:06,540
It was very straightforward user research,

496
00:24:06,580 --> 00:24:10,143
where it's can people progress through the game overall,

497
00:24:10,543 --> 00:24:12,004
and what does their progression curve look like,

498
00:24:12,444 --> 00:24:15,847
and is each piece of content working the way

499
00:24:15,887 --> 00:24:16,767
we think it should be working.

500
00:24:18,733 --> 00:24:20,754
It's not, again, not particularly sexy,

501
00:24:20,774 --> 00:24:22,815
but was the vast majority of what we did.

502
00:24:25,016 --> 00:24:26,357
So to go into some special topics,

503
00:24:27,698 --> 00:24:28,958
so Destiny is a class-based game.

504
00:24:29,038 --> 00:24:31,960
And we really had an intent that players

505
00:24:31,980 --> 00:24:34,481
would be able to recognize what class was coming at them

506
00:24:34,501 --> 00:24:35,562
in PVP instantly.

507
00:24:36,082 --> 00:24:38,503
That if something comes around the corner at you,

508
00:24:38,904 --> 00:24:40,985
if it's a warlock, you have to react very differently

509
00:24:41,025 --> 00:24:41,805
than if it's a titan.

510
00:24:42,565 --> 00:24:45,707
So we really wanted players to be able to instantly recognize

511
00:24:45,747 --> 00:24:46,087
what class.

512
00:24:46,107 --> 00:24:47,588
And there was a lot of work that went into that.

513
00:24:48,691 --> 00:24:51,754
on class silhouettes, class color schemes, and shapes.

514
00:24:53,215 --> 00:24:56,538
And of course, once those assets are actually built,

515
00:24:56,578 --> 00:24:57,679
they're very expensive to change.

516
00:24:57,719 --> 00:24:59,481
So we wanted to test them early, back

517
00:24:59,541 --> 00:25:02,223
when they're just concept art and they're very easy to change.

518
00:25:02,683 --> 00:25:05,006
So these are some examples of Destiny concept art

519
00:25:05,046 --> 00:25:05,966
we put in front of players.

520
00:25:06,627 --> 00:25:08,068
And so if you look at concept A there,

521
00:25:08,849 --> 00:25:10,530
essentially everybody said, yes, that's a hunter.

522
00:25:11,191 --> 00:25:11,932
They looked at that.

523
00:25:11,952 --> 00:25:15,014
They said, yep, earth tones, triangular silhouette, yep,

524
00:25:15,054 --> 00:25:15,475
that's a hunter.

525
00:25:16,641 --> 00:25:19,502
But character B, a lot of players misidentified as a warlock.

526
00:25:19,722 --> 00:25:20,622
Something about the shape.

527
00:25:20,962 --> 00:25:22,403
That was intended as a hunter concept,

528
00:25:22,963 --> 00:25:26,324
but something about the color scheme and the clean outlines

529
00:25:26,764 --> 00:25:29,064
tended to signal warlock to players.

530
00:25:30,325 --> 00:25:34,126
Likewise, character C here, players correctly,

531
00:25:34,466 --> 00:25:35,926
everybody correctly identified as a titan.

532
00:25:36,746 --> 00:25:37,666
But character D.

533
00:25:38,552 --> 00:25:40,372
a lot of people misidentified it as a hunter.

534
00:25:40,492 --> 00:25:42,593
Again, because the color scheme is something

535
00:25:42,633 --> 00:25:44,794
about the ragged cloth and the outline

536
00:25:45,514 --> 00:25:47,114
made people misidentify what class.

537
00:25:47,935 --> 00:25:49,555
So we were able to give a lot of feedback early

538
00:25:49,575 --> 00:25:53,376
to help the artists tune their designs before they actually

539
00:25:53,396 --> 00:25:53,976
built anything.

540
00:25:56,337 --> 00:25:59,338
Another topic we did research on was class regret.

541
00:25:59,858 --> 00:26:03,319
So like all RPGs, we asked players up front

542
00:26:03,339 --> 00:26:04,660
to choose what class they want to play.

543
00:26:06,446 --> 00:26:10,767
It's really stupid because we ask people to make that class choice at the moment where

544
00:26:10,787 --> 00:26:12,067
they know the least about the game.

545
00:26:13,028 --> 00:26:15,968
And we ask them to make a choice that's then going to affect the rest of their play for

546
00:26:15,988 --> 00:26:17,068
the entire experience.

547
00:26:18,169 --> 00:26:22,430
And we're pretty much setting them up for failure by asking them to do it that early,

548
00:26:22,470 --> 00:26:24,030
but that's when you have to make the choice.

549
00:26:24,590 --> 00:26:31,692
So early on we gave them class descriptions that were very lore-based, that talked about

550
00:26:31,732 --> 00:26:35,053
the theme of the class and the feel of the class and the fantasy of the class.

551
00:26:36,140 --> 00:26:40,600
But a lot of players ended up regretting

552
00:26:40,640 --> 00:26:42,861
what class they were playing by the time they were done.

553
00:26:43,081 --> 00:26:44,381
Because that lore didn't tell them

554
00:26:44,421 --> 00:26:46,341
a lot about how the class would actually play in combat.

555
00:26:47,182 --> 00:26:48,682
So we ended up moving to much more

556
00:26:48,722 --> 00:26:50,582
gameplay-based descriptions, where

557
00:26:50,662 --> 00:26:53,963
we were talking about the class's super abilities that

558
00:26:53,983 --> 00:26:56,083
really defined how they would play in battle.

559
00:26:56,923 --> 00:26:58,063
And players were much happier with this.

560
00:26:58,103 --> 00:27:00,724
And by the end of the testing, we

561
00:27:00,784 --> 00:27:02,644
had something like 85% of players

562
00:27:02,664 --> 00:27:04,365
saying they were very satisfied with their class

563
00:27:04,405 --> 00:27:05,105
by the end of development.

564
00:27:05,705 --> 00:27:06,665
by the end of their play session.

565
00:27:09,126 --> 00:27:14,968
So another topic we did research on was player recognition.

566
00:27:15,008 --> 00:27:17,509
So Destiny is what we call a shared world shooter.

567
00:27:18,709 --> 00:27:24,271
And it's a game where you run into other players

568
00:27:24,311 --> 00:27:25,151
no matter what you're doing.

569
00:27:25,171 --> 00:27:27,992
There really is no offline, single-player experience.

570
00:27:28,072 --> 00:27:29,973
Even if you play a single-player story mission,

571
00:27:30,433 --> 00:27:32,334
we're going to randomly matchmake you with people,

572
00:27:32,354 --> 00:27:33,894
and you'll just come around a rock,

573
00:27:33,954 --> 00:27:34,935
and there'll be other players.

574
00:27:35,573 --> 00:27:37,734
And that's awesome, and that's part of the magic of Destiny.

575
00:27:38,235 --> 00:27:39,095
And I'm actually going to play you

576
00:27:39,135 --> 00:27:42,156
a quick clip from one of our earliest play tests

577
00:27:42,176 --> 00:27:43,977
where that system was in action.

578
00:27:45,157 --> 00:27:47,038
There's no sound in this clip, so don't panic.

579
00:27:47,759 --> 00:27:49,519
So these are two players playing through in our lab.

580
00:27:50,420 --> 00:27:52,421
Player 11 there is a little tired from his adventures,

581
00:27:52,441 --> 00:27:54,741
and he's going to have a seat on the rock in Cosmodrome

582
00:27:54,781 --> 00:27:56,382
and look out over the vista.

583
00:27:58,263 --> 00:27:58,783
Yes, no.

584
00:28:00,384 --> 00:28:00,724
Yes.

