00:35:49,742 --> 00:35:51,363
Because the game wouldn't pause behind the menu.

743
00:35:51,763 --> 00:35:55,105
So we had to find a way to give feedback while they were still playing.

744
00:36:00,047 --> 00:36:02,348
So we added a contextual feedback system.

745
00:36:02,508 --> 00:36:05,970
So you basically press the touchpad and the face button and the data mining system would

746
00:36:06,030 --> 00:36:07,611
log a moment of saying...

747
00:36:08,462 --> 00:36:09,283
I'm frustrated here.

748
00:36:09,463 --> 00:36:12,407
And we log it with all appropriate sort of XYZ coordinates.

749
00:36:12,948 --> 00:36:15,171
We log who you were playing and where you were playing,

750
00:36:15,191 --> 00:36:17,434
all that kind of stuff, so we can analyze it later.

751
00:36:18,655 --> 00:36:19,496
And most importantly...

752
00:36:21,750 --> 00:36:22,610
connected to our video.

753
00:36:22,650 --> 00:36:27,054
So we could plot out maps of where people said they were frustrated, where they were

754
00:36:27,074 --> 00:36:31,058
lost, and importantly, where they were having awesome moments.

755
00:36:31,758 --> 00:36:36,042
We think of user research a lot of times as finding the problems in the game, but the

756
00:36:36,082 --> 00:36:38,984
best moments in user research are when you find the awesome moments in the game and get

757
00:36:39,024 --> 00:36:43,368
to tell the design team, we need more of this, this is working, that statue is awesome, how

758
00:36:43,388 --> 00:36:45,290
do we make sure everyone sees it?

759
00:36:47,380 --> 00:36:49,501
And so here's an example of an awesome moment of, OK,

760
00:36:49,521 --> 00:36:51,723
you catch your teammate being heroic right in front of you.

761
00:36:51,743 --> 00:36:55,366
And you can say, yes, OK, how do we give people more chances

762
00:36:55,406 --> 00:36:57,028
to see that kind of thing?

763
00:37:02,592 --> 00:37:04,634
We also imported our data into our world editor.

764
00:37:04,714 --> 00:37:09,098
So the environment artists and designers in Destiny

765
00:37:09,138 --> 00:37:11,840
work on a tool called Grognok, which is our world builder.

766
00:37:15,202 --> 00:37:17,324
A lot of times when we were making this incredibly rich

767
00:37:17,364 --> 00:37:21,047
data, but our designers had to come to us to get to the data.

768
00:37:21,087 --> 00:37:23,649
They had to come use sort of strange visualization tools

769
00:37:23,709 --> 00:37:26,071
that are really only well understood by user researchers.

770
00:37:26,811 --> 00:37:31,134
So we wanted to be a little more accessible.

771
00:37:31,795 --> 00:37:34,557
So we decided we were going to bring the data to them.

772
00:37:34,937 --> 00:37:38,380
And we imported into their world builder tool

773
00:37:38,620 --> 00:37:41,122
so they could look at it in the same tool they use every day,

774
00:37:41,743 --> 00:37:43,464
the one that they use to make changes to the game.

775
00:37:44,646 --> 00:37:50,151
And for me, this actually represented sort of how I believe fused research should work,

776
00:37:50,691 --> 00:37:54,294
is that we brought the data to them, we made it accessible to them, and it's our responsibility

777
00:37:54,714 --> 00:37:57,717
to put it in a format they can read and a place where they can easily access it.

778
00:37:59,939 --> 00:38:02,801
We also streamed our playtest from the lab out into the studio.

779
00:38:02,821 --> 00:38:03,602
Oh, yes.

780
00:38:03,762 --> 00:38:04,002
Yes.

781
00:38:04,102 --> 00:38:04,362
There we go.

782
00:38:05,343 --> 00:38:05,483
Yes.

783
00:38:05,503 --> 00:38:05,623
Yes.

784
00:38:07,545 --> 00:38:08,246
Yes.

785
00:38:08,266 --> 00:38:08,366
Yes.

786
00:38:08,386 --> 00:38:08,446
Yes.

787
00:38:08,466 --> 00:38:08,526
Yes.

788
00:38:08,546 --> 00:38:08,606
Yes.

789
00:38:09,867 --> 00:38:10,027
Yes.

790
00:38:11,890 --> 00:38:13,551
We also streamed our playtests out into the studio

791
00:38:14,051 --> 00:38:15,672
so everyone who didn't come down to the lab,

792
00:38:15,692 --> 00:38:16,672
and we certainly wouldn't want them all

793
00:38:16,712 --> 00:38:18,914
to come down to the lab at the same time,

794
00:38:19,014 --> 00:38:19,974
could watch from their desks.

795
00:38:20,815 --> 00:38:22,996
And this is the first game where we include face cams

796
00:38:23,236 --> 00:38:25,057
in all the playtest video we recorded.

797
00:38:25,617 --> 00:38:26,958
And I think that was really helpful

798
00:38:26,998 --> 00:38:28,779
in really inhumanizing the data.

799
00:38:29,319 --> 00:38:31,300
Because it's one thing to watch a player die,

800
00:38:31,360 --> 00:38:33,461
respawn, and go and charge back into battle.

801
00:38:33,882 --> 00:38:37,042
It's another thing to watch him die, see him bang his head on the desk,

802
00:38:37,642 --> 00:38:38,863
respawn and go back into battle.

803
00:38:39,343 --> 00:38:41,883
And just that moment of seeing what the human reaction was

804
00:38:41,963 --> 00:38:43,924
to what's going on in the game, I think really helps.

805
00:38:44,984 --> 00:38:47,184
Even if it's hard to quantify mathematically.

806
00:38:50,405 --> 00:38:53,586
One of the challenges we had, one of the other challenges we had,

807
00:38:53,646 --> 00:38:57,227
I'm sorry to be skipping around here so much, but a lot to get through.

808
00:38:58,413 --> 00:39:01,656
One of the challenges we had in Destiny was how we were going to test the endgame.

809
00:39:01,676 --> 00:39:05,540
So Destiny had this raid experience, where it launched, the first people to beat it took

810
00:39:05,820 --> 00:39:08,483
I believe over 10 hours to beat it, even the best teams in the world.

811
00:39:08,503 --> 00:39:14,809
And the problem is we had this endgame content that was designed for experts in a game that

812
00:39:14,849 --> 00:39:18,933
didn't exist yet, and there were no Destiny experts to test the content.

813
00:39:19,790 --> 00:39:22,172
So we end up breaking one of the cardinal rules of user

814
00:39:22,192 --> 00:39:23,773
research, and we brought participants back

815
00:39:23,813 --> 00:39:27,616
multiple times, which pretty much doesn't happen very often.

816
00:39:27,636 --> 00:39:28,936
Most of the time, we bring in participants,

817
00:39:29,297 --> 00:39:32,279
we get their initial reactions to the game, and we thank them.

818
00:39:32,739 --> 00:39:34,660
We give them their gratuity and let them go.

819
00:39:35,341 --> 00:39:36,622
But in this case, we were bringing back

820
00:39:36,682 --> 00:39:38,843
people who would, say, come in for a story playtest.

821
00:39:39,003 --> 00:39:41,245
One weekend, we'd bring them back a few weeks later

822
00:39:41,285 --> 00:39:42,886
to do a late game strike playtest,

823
00:39:43,286 --> 00:39:45,708
because we needed to have that expertise that they'd built up

824
00:39:45,748 --> 00:39:46,648
in the early experience.

825
00:39:48,185 --> 00:39:51,508
We also tested our raid by importing an entire shooter clan.

826
00:39:52,188 --> 00:39:56,593
This is the Gunslingers clan who graciously used their vacation days to fly out to the

827
00:39:56,613 --> 00:39:59,575
studio and play in our lab.

828
00:40:00,817 --> 00:40:05,721
They were really good sports, playing a very hard and many places broken raid experience

829
00:40:05,781 --> 00:40:06,242
early on.

830
00:40:07,283 --> 00:40:08,183
They didn't beat Atheon.

831
00:40:08,224 --> 00:40:11,707
They got them down to about 30 percent, I believe, which was pretty impressive for the

832
00:40:11,727 --> 00:40:14,009
first weekend and gave a lot of really valuable raid feedback.

833
00:40:16,015 --> 00:40:18,576
So now the game ships, we're collecting a lot of data

834
00:40:18,616 --> 00:40:20,537
on how people actually play Destiny out in the wild.

835
00:40:21,017 --> 00:40:25,980
And by and large, that data has been incredibly rewarding

836
00:40:26,360 --> 00:40:28,001
and very encouraging.

837
00:40:28,481 --> 00:40:31,263
So this is actually a graph of overall hours spent in Destiny

838
00:40:32,303 --> 00:40:32,923
by game mode.

839
00:40:33,764 --> 00:40:36,025
And people are generally playing in that sort of balanced way

840
00:40:36,065 --> 00:40:36,645
we want them to.

841
00:40:36,785 --> 00:40:40,467
And actually, this mix has been pretty consistent since launch,

842
00:40:41,828 --> 00:40:45,150
about the same proportion of time spent in various activities.

843
00:40:46,201 --> 00:40:48,743
However, there have been occasions where players have

844
00:40:48,883 --> 00:40:51,125
wandered off the path that we thought they were going to take,

845
00:40:52,846 --> 00:40:55,167
probably the most famous being the loot cave.

846
00:40:56,949 --> 00:40:58,790
So you can sort of see in this picture.

847
00:40:58,810 --> 00:41:01,832
Actually, just to check, how many people in this room

848
00:41:01,892 --> 00:41:02,833
shot into the loot cave?

849
00:41:03,834 --> 00:41:04,955
Yeah, that's what I figured.

850
00:41:05,755 --> 00:41:07,877
So I'll do a quick explanation for those of you

851
00:41:07,897 --> 00:41:08,377
who weren't there.

852
00:41:10,102 --> 00:41:12,263
Where this player is aiming, there's a little tiny point,

853
00:41:12,283 --> 00:41:14,463
there's a little tiny cave, and enemies would spawn out

854
00:41:14,483 --> 00:41:16,324
of that cave at a steady clip.

855
00:41:16,484 --> 00:41:18,324
Every few seconds, somebody would come out of the cave.

856
00:41:18,885 --> 00:41:19,765
And the players would shoot them.

857
00:41:19,825 --> 00:41:20,265
They'd die.

858
00:41:20,325 --> 00:41:21,465
They'd respawn and run out of the cave.

859
00:41:21,605 --> 00:41:23,086
And they were very weak enemies that

860
00:41:23,106 --> 00:41:24,226
didn't drop very good loot.

861
00:41:25,226 --> 00:41:28,527
But because players could stand at this great distance,

862
00:41:28,567 --> 00:41:31,148
as you see in this picture, and just ping

863
00:41:31,168 --> 00:41:32,308
into that cave for hours.

864
00:41:33,507 --> 00:41:34,948
Once they finally did run over there,

865
00:41:35,048 --> 00:41:37,010
even though there was a very low drop rate for loot,

866
00:41:37,591 --> 00:41:39,552
there would be this lovely hoard of treasure

867
00:41:39,693 --> 00:41:40,734
lying in the bottom of the cave.

868
00:41:42,455 --> 00:41:44,297
And players literally did this for hours.

869
00:41:44,517 --> 00:41:48,180
And the funny thing is we knew about this before launch.

870
00:41:48,241 --> 00:41:51,544
We knew that this was a potentially exploitable

871
00:41:51,584 --> 00:41:51,924
activity.

872
00:41:52,849 --> 00:41:55,609
But we didn't care, because we said,

873
00:41:55,629 --> 00:41:58,270
well, the actual drop rate per minute spent

874
00:41:58,910 --> 00:42:00,311
is not any different than anything else.

875
00:42:00,351 --> 00:42:03,052
So you actually will get less loot doing this per hour

876
00:42:03,572 --> 00:42:04,552
than just playing the game.

877
00:42:07,433 --> 00:42:10,294
But the players weren't actually doing the math that way.

878
00:42:10,354 --> 00:42:12,294
They were doing the math of, they

879
00:42:12,314 --> 00:42:13,415
weren't doing the loot per hour.

880
00:42:13,455 --> 00:42:15,355
They were looking at loot per effort.

881
00:42:16,215 --> 00:42:20,937
And this was so low effort that it felt like infinite free loot

882
00:42:21,417 --> 00:42:21,657
to them.

883
00:42:23,432 --> 00:42:28,279
And so, the interesting thing is this is actually pretty controversial in the player base itself,

884
00:42:28,400 --> 00:42:33,928
that this was actually the time of the loot cave was the highest peak for player reporting

885
00:42:33,948 --> 00:42:35,871
in Destiny, of players reporting each other for cheating.

886
00:42:37,180 --> 00:42:38,761
is a lot of players were reporting each other,

887
00:42:39,881 --> 00:42:41,322
people who didn't want to exploit the loot cave

888
00:42:41,342 --> 00:42:42,782
were reporting the people who were in the loot cave,

889
00:42:42,882 --> 00:42:43,783
who were shooting the loot cave.

890
00:42:44,603 --> 00:42:45,123
And the people who,

891
00:42:45,363 --> 00:42:46,664
and some people were even going so far

892
00:42:46,724 --> 00:42:48,024
as to go into the loot cave themselves

893
00:42:48,084 --> 00:42:49,205
and sit on the spawn point,

894
00:42:49,645 --> 00:42:51,706
which would prevent the enemies from spawning.

895
00:42:52,406 --> 00:42:55,027
And so the people who wanted to shoot into the loot cave

896
00:42:55,047 --> 00:42:56,227
were then reporting those people

897
00:42:56,267 --> 00:42:56,807
for being,

898
00:42:58,128 --> 00:42:59,769
obstructing their chosen play style.

899
00:43:01,649 --> 00:43:02,910
So this wasn't just a case where sort of,

900
00:43:03,476 --> 00:43:04,596
Bungie hated it and didn't fix it.

901
00:43:04,856 --> 00:43:06,717
There were a lot of players who didn't like this as well.

902
00:43:07,237 --> 00:43:08,397
But we did patch the loot cave.

903
00:43:08,417 --> 00:43:09,857
There actually is a memorial in the cave

904
00:43:09,897 --> 00:43:10,757
if you haven't been back.

905
00:43:11,278 --> 00:43:13,498
There is a memorial that's worth visiting and looking at.

906
00:43:15,738 --> 00:43:18,519
And since then, we've also found a number of other loot caves.

907
00:43:18,539 --> 00:43:21,980
So this is a top-down map of one of our destinations.

908
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:23,460
And those red spots over there on the right

909
00:43:23,780 --> 00:43:27,381
are some minor loot caves that we discovered algorithmically

910
00:43:28,761 --> 00:43:30,922
before they got on YouTube or Reddit or whatever.

911
00:43:32,200 --> 00:43:34,561
and we were able to patch them before they became popular.

912
00:43:36,441 --> 00:43:38,782
And so we're constantly doing this with, pretty much throughout the game,

913
00:43:38,822 --> 00:43:42,423
of looking for moments where players are beating things very quickly,

914
00:43:42,703 --> 00:43:44,344
taking too long, taking too short,

915
00:43:44,384 --> 00:43:47,405
and looking for places where the experience isn't what we expected.

916
00:43:48,065 --> 00:43:50,066
So we can then investigate and find out what's going on.

917
00:43:50,506 --> 00:43:52,046
One of the great things about the modern age

918
00:43:52,267 --> 00:43:54,387
is that everything is on YouTube and Twitch,

919
00:43:54,887 --> 00:43:57,288
so if you can find some strange play style in the data,

920
00:43:57,688 --> 00:43:59,749
somebody out there has put it online for you to watch.

921
00:44:01,377 --> 00:44:03,158
That's a wonderful resource for you as researchers.

922
00:44:05,218 --> 00:44:07,739
So a couple of lessons I learned over the course of this.

923
00:44:07,779 --> 00:44:09,039
And I'm going to say we here.

924
00:44:09,079 --> 00:44:11,439
I'm not speaking for Bungie in this case, in this slide.

925
00:44:11,479 --> 00:44:13,240
I'm speaking for myself and my research team.

926
00:44:14,440 --> 00:44:16,240
Or, OK, mostly for myself.

927
00:44:16,300 --> 00:44:18,421
I won't get my research team in trouble.

928
00:44:21,021 --> 00:44:23,802
So I absolutely underestimated our blessings on Halo.

929
00:44:24,062 --> 00:44:27,743
That we didn't realize how good we had at the time.

930
00:44:29,273 --> 00:44:29,953
as I spoke earlier.

931
00:44:30,573 --> 00:44:32,234
We underestimated how rabid our fans would be.

932
00:44:32,274 --> 00:44:33,734
So one of the first questions I got

933
00:44:33,855 --> 00:44:35,575
was when I started at Bungie was,

934
00:44:35,975 --> 00:44:37,576
so how much are people going to play the game?

935
00:44:38,396 --> 00:44:40,397
And they wanted to say, OK, we want

936
00:44:40,637 --> 00:44:43,198
to drop a certain amount of loot per week.

937
00:44:43,658 --> 00:44:45,278
So how many hours per week are people going to play

938
00:44:45,298 --> 00:44:46,859
so we can adjust drop rates to get people

939
00:44:46,919 --> 00:44:47,859
about the right experience?

940
00:44:48,720 --> 00:44:53,141
And I based it on Halo and underestimated by about 50%.

941
00:44:56,446 --> 00:45:01,568
Our fans on Destiny are just way more enthusiastic than I think anybody anticipated they would be.

942
00:45:04,589 --> 00:45:07,891
We really didn't correctly manage the transition to the Elder Games.

943
00:45:07,951 --> 00:45:12,152
So Destiny has an early game where you're leveling up through experience points,

944
00:45:12,172 --> 00:45:14,153
you're leveling up your character, then you get to level 20,

945
00:45:14,233 --> 00:45:15,594
and you start leveling up through your gear.

946
00:45:16,614 --> 00:45:19,035
And a lot of people missed that transition.

947
00:45:19,055 --> 00:45:21,276
That's not intuitive for a lot of shooter players.

948
00:45:23,879 --> 00:45:25,420
And when I say a lot of people, I mean something like 4%

949
00:45:25,560 --> 00:45:27,222
of players got stuck at level 20.

950
00:45:27,862 --> 00:45:30,384
They just never quite made that jump to the elder game

951
00:45:30,444 --> 00:45:31,125
progression system.

952
00:45:33,247 --> 00:45:34,628
We knew that there might be a problem there,

953
00:45:34,648 --> 00:45:36,349
and we did some work on it, but we never fully

954
00:45:36,389 --> 00:45:37,550
smoothed it out before release.

955
00:45:41,173 --> 00:45:43,355
And I think probably the biggest screw up,

956
00:45:44,436 --> 00:45:45,897
I thought players would hate power in PvP.

957
00:45:46,758 --> 00:45:50,220
that every playtest we did on PvP and Destiny in the lab,

958
00:45:50,940 --> 00:45:53,881
players hated the concept of level in PvP.

959
00:45:54,542 --> 00:45:55,602
That the idea that they would get

960
00:45:55,662 --> 00:45:57,723
killed by someone who was higher level than them,

961
00:45:57,763 --> 00:45:59,844
and they would get really angry that they

962
00:45:59,864 --> 00:46:01,144
were in this unfair match.

963
00:46:02,265 --> 00:46:04,165
And they wouldn't even get angry at the other player.

964
00:46:04,185 --> 00:46:05,146
They would get angry at us.

965
00:46:05,786 --> 00:46:07,127
They would say, screw you, Bungie.

966
00:46:07,367 --> 00:46:08,987
You put me in a game with that guy.

967
00:46:09,988 --> 00:46:11,648
Your matchmaking system failed me

968
00:46:11,988 --> 00:46:13,649
and put me in a situation where I couldn't win.

969
00:46:14,209 --> 00:46:15,890
And they got really upset with us.

970
00:46:16,818 --> 00:46:19,279
Even in a playtest where the power didn't matter,

971
00:46:19,299 --> 00:46:22,120
and again, at all for stats,

972
00:46:22,500 --> 00:46:24,061
but just we had the numbers over your head,

973
00:46:24,441 --> 00:46:26,242
players got angry about power in PvP.

974
00:46:26,502 --> 00:46:28,903
It was just a concept that players hated in the lab.

975
00:46:29,863 --> 00:46:31,203
So of course, in our first Iron Banner,

976
00:46:31,243 --> 00:46:36,285
we started out with a very minor, minor effect of power in PvP,

977
00:46:36,365 --> 00:46:37,826
saying, okay, we're gonna let it matter a little bit

978
00:46:37,906 --> 00:46:38,666
and see what happens.

979
00:46:40,347 --> 00:46:41,527
And thinking players would hate it,

980
00:46:41,667 --> 00:46:43,768
and actually the overwhelming response was

981
00:46:45,691 --> 00:46:46,411
this should be worse.

982
00:46:46,531 --> 00:46:50,373
I mean, a level 30 should totally destroy me in PvP.

983
00:46:51,393 --> 00:46:52,694
And this was just startling to us.

984
00:46:52,734 --> 00:46:55,595
And there was something funny happened in that transition

985
00:46:55,715 --> 00:46:58,316
from the character I was, the throwaway character they

986
00:46:58,336 --> 00:47:01,217
were playing in the lab, and the real character and gear

987
00:47:01,237 --> 00:47:02,358
they'd earned out in the real world.

988
00:47:02,778 --> 00:47:04,178
That once it was their real gear,

